## Summary

DNA sequence establishes the inherited framework of biological systems, but it does not by itself specify the molecular state of a cell. That state emerges through transcription and RNA processing: transcription initiation, RNA 3′-end formation, alternative splicing, RNA editing, polyadenylation, and the selection of coding and untranslated regions.

These processes generate distinct RNA isoforms from the same genomic locus. Each isoform is a linked molecular entity in which an observed 5′ boundary, inferred promoter usage, exon composition, predicted coding sequence, candidate editing events, and regulatory regions occur together on the same transcript. Preserving those relationships can be important because different isoforms may support different protein products, differ in stability or localization, or respond differently to cellular regulation.

Conventional short-read RNA sequencing has transformed biology, but it typically fragments transcripts before sequencing. The resulting reads provide highly accurate local sequence information, while end-to-end structures must often be inferred computationally. Long-read sequencing can preserve more of the original transcript structure, but currently involves different trade-offs in instrumentation, throughput, depth, accuracy, cost, and workflow.

Phaeno’s PSeq technology is designed to preserve source-molecule identity through a short-read sequencing workflow. Reads assigned to the same captured molecular template can therefore be grouped before transcript assembly, converting an otherwise unconstrained reconstruction problem into a molecule-constrained one. Molecular identity narrows the search space; complete reconstruction still depends on the coverage, overlap, reference information, and boundary evidence available for that molecule.

In this series, Phaeno uses **phased sequencing** to describe sequencing architectures that preserve linkage among observations originating from the same source molecule. This usage is distinct from the common genomic meaning of phasing variants into haplotypes and overlaps conceptually with terms such as molecule-aware sequencing, linked reads, read clouds, and barcoded fragment reconstruction.

This article explains why that distinction matters. Part 2 will describe how PSeq preserves source-molecule identity, and Part 3 will examine the potential value of molecule-resolved transcript data in biological discovery, translational research, and machine learning.

## DNA sequence alone does not specify cellular state

The Human Genome Project established a reference sequence for the human genome and provided an essential foundation for modern biology. It also helped clarify the limits of sequence information considered in isolation.

Cells with nearly identical genomes can adopt markedly different structures and functions. A hepatocyte, neuron, lymphocyte, and epithelial cell generally contain the same inherited DNA sequence, yet differ extensively in morphology, metabolism, signaling, and behavior. These differences arise from regulatory processes that determine which portions of the genome are used, how they are transcribed, and how the resulting RNAs are processed.

RNA occupies a central position in this process. It is both an intermediate between DNA and protein and, in many cases, a functional molecular species in its own right. Messenger RNAs encode proteins, while ribosomal, transfer, micro-, long noncoding, and other classes of RNA contribute directly to translation, regulation, genome organization, and cellular signaling.

Even within protein-coding genes, the relationship between a genomic locus and its biological products is not one-to-one. A single locus may produce multiple transcripts through combinations of:

- alternative transcription initiation;
- alternative splicing;
- alternative cleavage and polyadenylation;
- RNA editing;
- variation in untranslated regions;
- differential transcript stability and degradation.

The resulting transcripts may encode distinct protein sequences, alter the abundance of a protein, change where an RNA is localized, or affect its translation and degradation. The biological output of a gene therefore depends not only on whether the gene is expressed, but also on which transcripts are produced and in what proportions.

For this reason, RNA isoforms should not be treated merely as interchangeable measurements of gene activity. Each transcript is a linked arrangement of sequence and regulatory features that exists as a physical molecule.

## The transcript as a linked unit of information

A transcript may contain several biologically meaningful features simultaneously:

- its observed 5′ transcript boundary;
- its exon and splice-junction structure;
- its predicted open reading frame or coding potential;
- sequence variants or candidate RNA-editing events;
- its 5′ and 3′ untranslated regions;
- its observed 3′ transcript boundary or cleavage and polyadenylation site.

The significance of any one feature may depend on the others with which it occurs.

A sequence variant, for example, may be present only in transcripts with a particular observed 5′ boundary or inferred promoter usage. An exon-skipping event may alter the predicted reading frame in one transcript context but not another. A 3′ untranslated region may contain regulatory motifs that affect the stability, localization, or translation of a specific isoform. Two transcripts from the same gene may therefore differ functionally even when they share most of their sequence.

This creates a phasing problem.

In sequencing, **phasing** means determining which sequence features occur together on the same physical molecule. The concept is familiar in genomics, where variants may be assigned to maternal or paternal chromosomes. In transcriptomics, the same principle applies to combinations of splice junctions, observed transcript boundaries, sequence variants, candidate editing events, and regulatory regions.

Knowing that two features are present in a sample is not equivalent to knowing that they occur on the same transcript.

That distinction becomes especially important for genes that produce many overlapping isoforms. If several transcripts share exons and splice junctions, short sequence fragments may be compatible with multiple end-to-end structures. The local observations can be correct while the global arrangement remains ambiguous.

