Whether PSeq achieves these objectives across transcript classes, sample types, and abundance ranges is a question for analytical and experimental validation. Relevant benchmarks will include sensitivity, specificity, consensus accuracy relative to both captured cDNA and original RNA controls, transcript completeness under predefined criteria, isoform quantification, reproducibility, throughput, cost, and comparison with both short- and long-read methods.

Those studies are essential because molecule-resolved sequencing is useful only if molecular identity is preserved accurately and the resulting reconstructions reflect the molecules present in the original sample.

## Conclusion

RNA is not simply a transient copy of DNA. It is a diverse population of molecular species in which predicted coding sequence, splice structure, observed transcript boundaries, regulatory regions, and sequence variation occur in linked combinations.

Conventional RNA sequencing measures this population with exceptional scale and accuracy, but fragmentation often separates features that originally belonged to the same molecule. Computational methods can reconstruct many transcript structures, yet ambiguity remains when multiple isoforms share the same local sequence evidence.

Long-read sequencing restores much of this connectivity by reading extended molecules directly. PSeq takes a different approach: preserving source-molecule identity through a short-read workflow and using that identity to constrain transcript assembly.

The potential significance of this approach is straightforward. If biological function depends on linked features within individual RNA molecules, then preserving captured molecular templates as units of measurement may reveal information that is obscured by fragment-level or gene-level summaries. Whether a reconstruction is complete, biologically faithful, or functionally important remains a separate question.

