## Summary

In this series, Phaeno uses **phased sequencing** to describe sequencing architectures that preserve linkage among observations originating from the same source molecule. The idea is simple: fragments are much more informative when their molecular origin remains known.

Conventional short-read RNA sequencing usually fragments and pools many transcripts before sequencing. The resulting reads can be accurate, abundant, and highly useful, but the experiment generally does not retain a direct record of which distant fragments came from the same captured molecular template. End-to-end transcript structures must therefore be inferred from overlapping evidence collected across a mixed population.

PSeq is designed to change that measurement architecture. Molecular information is associated with each successfully captured RNA-derived cDNA molecule before short-fragment library generation. That information is intended to remain recoverable on the resulting reads, allowing reads from the same captured template to be grouped into molecule-specific sets before assembly.

The result is not a long read. It is a collection of short reads assigned to a shared captured template. Assembly can therefore be performed within a source-molecule boundary rather than across an undifferentiated pool of transcript fragments, but reconstruction still depends on coverage continuity, overlap, reference guidance, and transcript-boundary evidence.

## What source-molecule identity means

Source-molecule identity is the experimental information that connects a sequencing observation to an individual captured RNA-derived molecular template.

In a cDNA workflow, that observable template is a reverse-transcribed representation of a starting RNA molecule, not the original RNA observed directly. Reverse transcription may be incomplete, may introduce substitutions or template switching, may produce more than one product, or may fail to produce a recoverable product. An observed cDNA end therefore provides evidence about an RNA boundary but is not automatically proof of the native biological end.

It is related to, but distinct from, ordinary sample indexing. A sample index identifies the specimen or library that produced a read. Source-molecule information operates at a finer level: it distinguishes individual captured molecular templates within that specimen or library.

It is also distinct from transcript annotation. An annotation may state that a read is compatible with a known gene or isoform. Source-molecule identity states that a particular set of reads originated from the same captured molecular template, whether or not that template matches an existing annotation.

<ArticleCallout>
  <em>Sample identity answers which specimen a read came from. Source-molecule identity answers which captured RNA-derived molecular template within that specimen a read was assigned to.</em>
</ArticleCallout>

This distinction matters because two RNA-derived molecular templates from the same gene may have different splice junctions, observed transcript boundaries, sequence variants, candidate editing events, or untranslated regions. Once fragments from those templates are mixed without a recoverable source relationship, their end-to-end arrangements become a computational inference problem.

## Why identity must be established before fragmentation

Fragmentation separates sequence features that were originally connected on the same molecule. A splice junction near the observed 5′ boundary, a sequence variant in a predicted coding region, and a 3′ untranslated region may all be observed accurately, yet nothing in the fragment sequences alone necessarily proves that those features occurred together.

If molecular origin is established before fragmentation and carried into the sequencing library, the fragments can remain related even after the physical molecule has been divided. The connection is informational rather than spatial.

Four requirements follow from that design:

<ArticleKeyPoints
