## Identity constrains assembly; it does not solve it automatically

Source-molecule identity changes the search space available to an assembler. In conventional transcript assembly, many fragments from many transcripts may be compatible with the same gene. The algorithm must identify one or more transcript models that explain the pooled evidence.

In a molecule-constrained workflow, the assembler receives a smaller set of reads believed to originate from one captured molecular template. The question changes from “Which population of transcripts explains these fragments?” to “How do these fragments fit together within this captured template, given the coverage, overlap, reference information, and boundary evidence available?”

That constraint can reduce ambiguity, but it does not eliminate every failure mode. A molecule-specific set containing disconnected islands of coverage may still support multiple reconstructions—or no complete reconstruction.

Here, **transcript completeness** refers to a predefined analytical criterion and should not be assumed solely from assignment of reads to one molecule. The criterion should state whether it requires observed 5′ and 3′ boundaries, a complete splice chain, minimum coverage, an end-to-end contiguous consensus, or reference-supported interpolation.

